{{Infobox Theatre |name = Prince's Theatre |image = |image_size = |caption = |address = Oxford Street |city = [[Manchester]] |country = England |designation = |latitude = |longitude = |architect = [[Edward Salomons]]<ref name=RudyardWykePP47-48/> |owner = |capacity = 1,590, increased to 1,890 in 1869 |type = |opened = 1864 |yearsactive = |rebuilt = |closed = 1940 |othernames = |production = |demolished = |website = }} The '''Prince's Theatre''' in Oxford Street, [[Manchester]], England, was built at a cost of £20,000 in 1864. Under the artistic and managerial leadership of [[Charles Alexander Calvert|Charles Calvert]], "Manchester's most celebrated actor-manager", it soon became a great popular success. The theatre's first production, Shakespeare's ''[[The Tempest]]'', took place on 15&nbsp;October 1864;<ref name=RudyardWykePP47-48>{{Harvnb|Rudyard|Wyke|1994|pp=47–48}}</ref> Calvert himself played [[Prospero]] and his wife took the role of [[Miranda (The Tempest)|Miranda]]. ''The Times'' newspaper of 18&nbsp;October reported that the 1,590-seat theatre "was exceedingly well filled", and declared the evening "a brilliant success".<ref name=Times1864>{{citation |title=The Drama in Manchester |url=http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/346/292/133531392w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS202547026&dyn=8!xrn_3_0_CS202547026&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib |newspaper=The Times |date=18 October 1864 |accessdate=29 December 2010}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> The theatre subsequently became synonymous with Calvert's elaborate and historically accurate Shakespearian productions.<ref name=RudyardWykePP47-48/>
The theatre's interior was extensively rebuilt by [[Alfred Darbyshire]] in 1869. The work included the addition of 300&nbsp;seats,<ref name=RudyardWykePP47-48/> and featured a frieze over the [[proscenium]] painted by [[Henry Stacy Marks]] showing Shakespeare flanked by muses and his principal characters. The Prince's was the first theatre to introduce [[tip-up seat]]s and "early doors" tickets, which for a premium allowed patrons to enter the theatre early, to avoid the usual opening-time crush.<ref name=RudyardWykePP47-48/>
The years after the First World War saw a decline in the theatre's fortunes, and by the 1930s the increasing competition from cinema was threatening its viability. The final performance took place in April 1940, after which the building was sold to the [[ABC Cinemas|ABC]] cinema company, who intended to replace it with a large cinema complex. Although the theatre was demolished shortly afterwards, the intervention of the Second World War meant that the cinema was never built; the site is now occupied by Peter House, a large office complex completed in 1958.<ref name=RudyardWykePP47-48/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manchesterconfidential.co.uk/Culture/Architecture/The-Good-the-Standard-and-the-Ugly-Peter-House |title=The Good, the Standard and the Ugly: Peter House &#124; Architecture |publisher=Manchester Confidential |date=23 November 2009 |accessdate=3 April 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref>
